One America, Two Citizens
New York—As I write this article, officials across the United States are still counting the votes in the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
Once the final results are determined, recounts and legal challenges are sure to follow.
This is to be expected in this highly competitive election with record voter turnout.
Only U.S. citizens can vote to elect the President of the United States, but this choice affects people across the country.
If determining the election results at this point is premature, then discussing the implications of this election for the world's most powerful nation is not.
From a positive perspective, the United States remains a strong democratic nation.
Despite the practical limitations related to the pandemic, voter participation remains high.
This process seems to be proceeding as planned.
Moreover, violent incidents are rare.
Courts are investigating decisions by the United States Postal Service that appear to be motivated by political considerations, hindering the delivery of ballots from regions where the majority of expected votes come from Democrats.
The current president of the United States, Donald Trump, made an unfounded announcement of victory on Tuesday evening, which received little response, while his request to stop counting votes (at least in states where he was leading) seemed to be ignored.
However, it is concerning that the divide among American voters remains significant.
The votes of the two candidates were almost equal.
It is no surprise that this division is likely to lead to a split in the government.
If the current trend continues, the Democratic Party will win the White House and continue to control the House of Representatives, while the Republican Party will continue to control the Senate.
The governorships and state legislative seats are almost evenly split between the two parties (with the Republican Party holding a slight advantage).
The Democratic Party's expected "blue wave" did not materialize.
Biden is likely to win the popular vote by a large margin, securing approximately four to five million votes out of nearly 160 million.
But the Republican Party held onto many seats that were predicted to flip, while the Democratic Party actually lost seats in the House of Representatives.
This outcome does not come from strong authorization, nor does it stem from political adjustments.
Donald Trump's polling situation was very strong, receiving five million more votes than in 2016, making him the second-highest vote-getter in U.S. presidential election history and surpassing any previous winner.
Notably, this occurred against the backdrop of record-high daily new coronavirus cases exceeding 100,000 and over 1,000 deaths.
At the moment when the consequences of his government's inadequate handling of the pandemic had become most severe, nearly half of the voters turned to support him.
Even if Trump lost, which seems highly likely, he would still retain significant influence, especially if he remained in the public eye, which also seems likely.
Even if he himself does not run, he is likely to have a significant influence on the selection of the Republican Party's nominee in the 2024 presidential election.
The Republican Party will be far removed from the party of former Presidents Bush or Reagan.
Trumpism — a form of modern American populism — will still be a powerful force.
Unsurprisingly, despite Trump offering no evidence, he made every effort to portray himself as virtuous and upright, attempted to undermine the legitimacy of the election results, and accused there being fraudulent activities.
Many of his supporters will reject the legitimacy of Biden's presidency.
Trump is very likely to never concede and will certainly not attend the inauguration ceremony of his successor.
Applying the words of Will Rogers, Trump has never encountered a norm he couldn't break.
Americans are increasingly living in different worlds.
They will categorize themselves into different communities and regions based on shared views.
And each world tends to watch its own cable television channels, listen to its own radio stations and podcasts, and visit its own websites.
The absence of a national citizenship curriculum has facilitated the differentiation among people of different generations.
It is worth emphasizing that national divisions are, in most cases, not along economic lines.
People from all social strata voted for both candidates, and the voting patterns by population, gender, and race did not swing overwhelmingly in one direction as many had predicted.
Their differences mainly lie in the remedies.
Educational level is clearly an indicator of political orientation, as is geographical location. Republican voters tend to reside in suburban and rural areas, while Democratic voters tend to reside in urban areas.
However, the role of culture in American politics may be greater than any other factor.
In fact, foreign policy seemed to be relatively unimportant in the campaign, except for mobilizing specific districts, such as the large Cuban and Venezuelan communities in South Florida.
In such a context, it is difficult to gain public support for major reforms to the way presidential elections or government operations are conducted.
This situation is no different from the reform of the United Nations Security Council.
Many people believe that the current system has serious flaws and lacks representativeness, but it is impossible to reach a consensus on reforms because any potential solution would benefit some while harming others.
It is no surprise that those who would suffer losses from the change will resist the change.
This will make governance difficult.
This largely depends on the assessment of Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell and his willingness and ability to cooperate with the future President Biden.
Collaboration will also require Biden to make compromises, which is certain to face resistance from members of his party with strong ideological commitments.
Democrats once attempted to dismiss everything that Trump and his representatives stood for in a sharp manner.
But they were not successful.
And the Republicans are seeking an election that recognizes Trump.
And this also did not go as they had hoped.
On the contrary, the election reveals a nation and two categories of citizens.
They will have to coexist; but whether they can coexist remains to be seen.
